3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.0b90c993-9971-42fc-b049-730c432c9bc3.description=
Crawls through a set of URLs starting from a URL (or list of URLs) provided as input. The flow visits the web pages in the baseURL input and, if it is allowed (recursionDepth > 0), will also visit in a recursive manner the URLs that are referred (in hyperlinks) by the previously visited pages. This process repeats upto a certain level of recursion specified using the recursionDepth input - this prevents the flow from crawling endlessly. The flow will only test a URL a single time. The tested URLs are classified by the flow as good, slow or bad and passed in the corresponding results.

Inputs\:
    baseURL - The list of URLs to be tested. Semicolon (;) is used as delimiter for this list.
    recurse - Specifies whether the crawler will recurse. If set to "Yes" it will recurse to a depth specified by the recursionDepth numeric input. If set to "No" the crawler will not recurse regardless of the recursionDepth input.
Valid values\: Yes, No.
Default value\: No.
    recursionDepth - The depth to which the crawler will continue to test linked pages.
Default value\: no recursion limit - this means that the crawler is allowed to recurse endlessly if the recurse input is "Yes".
Valid values\: natural numbers.    
    timeout - How many milliseconds a page is given to respond before it is considered slow.
Default value\: 0 - this means that there is no response timeout and a page is considered "good" if it responds successfully.
    allowedDomains - A semicolon delimited list of domains that the flow is allowed to crawl through. This does not need to include the domain of baseURL.
    username - The username to use for authentication to the URLs.
    password - The password to use for basic authentication to the URLs.
    proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the URLs.
    proxyPort - A port on the proxy to connect to.
    proxyUsername - A username to use when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - A password to use when connecting to the proxy.
    followRedirects - Specifies whether or not the "get" command should automatically follow redirects.
Default value\: false.
    trustAllRoots - Enables weak security over SSL. An SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false.
    trustKeystore - URL of the truststore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
    trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore.
    characterSet - The characterSet for HTTP Get request and response.
Default value\: UTF-8.
    keystore - URL of the keystore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS client  authentication is not to be used.
    keystorePassword - Password to unlock the keystore.
    authType - The authentication type that this operation uses when trying to execute the request on the target server. 
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
    useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value. 
Default value\: true.
    userAgent - If the HTTP header USER_AGENT needs to be overridden, pass in the value here.
    kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty the kdc (Key Distribution Center) and realm will get their values from the full domain name which is obtained from the url of the web server.
    headerNamesList - A list containing the names of headers that should be used for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - A list containing the values of headers that should be used for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - A list containing the names of query parameters that should be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - A list containing the values of query parameters that should be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - A delimiter that separates the elements in the names and values lists.
Default value\: , (comma).

Responses\:
    success - The web pages were tested and classified.
    failure - The web pages could not be tested and classified.

Results\:
    badURLs - A semicolon delimited list of URLs that did not respond, or responded with an HTTP error.
    slowURLs - A semicolon delimited List of URLs that took longer than timeout milliseconds to respond. This result will be empty if timeout input is 0.
    goodURLs - A semicolon delimited List of URLs that were tested successfully and before the timeout expired.
    toTest - A list of all the URLs that were tested.
    errorMessage - If an error occurred, an informational message that may help determine the cause of the error.

Note\:
1. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, consider using the “queryNamesList” and “queryValuesList” inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the url (Example\: http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2). If you specify the same query parameter both through the "queryNamesList" and through the url input, then the value from the "queryValuesList" list will be used and not the one included in the url.
2. Currently, the only supported application server when using form-based authentication is Apache Tomcat.
3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.131dd31c-e9da-4e1f-90e1-337a8e90f906.description=
Adds a value into the global context (available to all parent and child flows)

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the context variable to use
myValue - the value to assign the context variable

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, $myValue];
3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.45938471-7fa8-4fc8-890c-67e23136f37c.prompt=Enter a value for notifyData 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.544d5cc6-67fa-4ba4-acb1-a12ee34b0449.prompt=URL to start check from. 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.602e7fa2-5565-45b4-856e-a6d16551da26.prompt=domains to recurse into?(semicolon delimited) 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.7b72ff67-838a-438b-9ecd-4e36eb4b1bcb.description=
Allows a user to select how they should be notified of the outcome of a flow, and shows them a message in that way.

Inputs\:
notifyData -  The text of the notification message.
notifyMethod - The method of notification (Write to File, Email, Display or None). This value is case-insensitive.
subject - A description of what the notification is about. 
destination - The destination of the notification (email address or filename). This field is required when notifyMethod is Email or Write to File.
notificationServer - The email server to send the notification through. This field is required when notifyMethod is Email.
from - The originator of the message (email "from" address).This field is required when notifyMethod is Email.
serverPort - The port the service to notify on the server is running on. This field used when notifyMethod is Email, and it is optional (it defaults to 25 if not specified).
htmlEmail - Default value is true. The value should be true if the email is in rich text/html format. The value should be false to send the email in plain text format.

Responses\:
success - The user was notified.
failure - Notification failed.

As mentioned above, some inputs are required for certain types of notification methods. In order to schedule a flow that in turn uses this flow, all of the required fields for the given notification method must be supplied, or else the flow will not be able to execute to completion. For example, if "notifyMethod" is "File", then the "destination" input must also be specified.
3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.aa54db8b-a89c-4325-8d35-2abd403f2b45.description=
Retrieves a url, and measures the amount of time the retrieval took.

Inputs\:
timeout - How many milliseconds are considered an acceptable retrieval time. If 0, than all retrieval times are acceptable.
url - url to measure the time to get.
username - The username to use for basic authentication to the url
password - The password to use for basic authentication to the url
authType - The authentication type that this operation uses when trying to execute the request on the target server. Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty the kdc (Key Distribution Center) and realm will get their values from the full domain name which is obtained from the url of the web server.
useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value. Default value\: true.
followRedirects - specifies whether or not the get command should automatically follow redirects. Default value is set to false.
proxy - a proxy to use when accessing the web site.
proxyPort - a port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - a username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - a password to use when connecting to the proxy.
encodeURL - Perform URL encoding. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value. Default value\: false.
userAgent - If the HTTP header USER_AGENT needs to be overridden, pass in the value here.
characterSet - the characterSet for HTTP Get request and response. Default is UTF-8.
trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.Default value\: false.
keystore - URL of the keystore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS client  authentication is not to be used.
keystorePassword - Password to unlock the keystore.
trustKeystore - URL of the truststore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore.
localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. For example,  en or ja.
localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.
headerNamesList - A list containing the names of headers that should be used for the request. Example\: Accept,Content-Type
headerValuesList - A list containing the values of headers that should be used for the request. Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
queryNamesList - A list containing the names of query parameters that should be used for the request. Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
queryValuesList - A list containing the values of query parameters that should be used for the request. Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
delimiter - A delimiter that separates the elements in the names and values lists. Default value\: , (comma).

Responses\:
success - web page was retrieved in less than timeout milliseconds.
failure - web page could not be retrieved.
diagnosed - The web page was retrieved, but it took more than timeout milliseconds.

Returns\:
The number of milliseconds it took to retrieve the page.

Extra Results\:
urls - A semicolon delimited list of links from the given url.

Notes\:
1. You can use keytool to import an ssl certificate in a keystore. For example to import a certificate in the Java cacerts keystore you should run\: keytool -import -file c\:/../.cer -alias  -keystore %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts -keystorepass changeit. If the keystore does not exist the command will try to create a new one containing only your certificate.
2. You can use keytool to create a certificate chain through the following command\: 
   keytool -genkey -dname "cn\=Mark Jones, ou\=JavaSoft, o\=Sun, c\=US" 
      -alias business -keypass kpi135 -keystore C\:\working\mykeystore 
      -storepass ab987c -validity 180
It creates a certificate chain in a new keystore containing only one certificate. This command is useful in case of ssl client authentication because the KeyManager ignores any certificates which are not included in a certificate chain.
3. If trustAllRoots \= false and trustKeystore is empty, the operation will try to use the default trust store with the password "changeit". (i.e.  %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts) 
4. If you need to specify the request header fields, consider using the "headerNamesList" and "headerValuesList" inputs. The operation also accepts hidden inputs whose names begin with "header_", but this deprecated. You can add multiple headers.  For example, add an input name called "header_Content-Type" with a value as "text/html" and/or an input name called "header_Content-Length" with a value as "348".  The operation will strip off the "header_" prefix from the input name first, and the "Content-Type" and/or "Content-Length" header should be created with the value you specify. If you specify the same header both through the "headerNamesList" and through a "header_" hidden input, then the value from the "headerValuesList" list will be used and not the hidden input's value.
5. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, consider using the “queryNamesList” and “queryValuesList” inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the url (Example\: http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2). If you specify the same query parameter both through the "queryNamesList" and through the url input, then the value from the "queryValuesList" list will be used and not the one included in the url.
6. Currently, the only supported application server when using form-based authentication is Apache Tomcat.
3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.afd88ffd-19da-45fa-b927-6eb6955f675a.prompt=Notification option\: 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.b7a853ec-da7e-40db-80da-d510064ec614.description=Iterates through a list of values. Inputs\: list - The list to iterate through. separator - A delimiter that separates elements in the list. Returns\: The current element of the list, if the response is has more Responses\: has more - Another value was in the list, and has been returned. has no more - The iterator has gone fully through the list. This response will only be returned once per iteration through the list, a subsequent call to the Iterator will restart the Iteration through the list. failure - failed to process the list. Note\: Where the iterator is in the list is tracked by each step's unique id. Therefore you can iterate on the same list from multiple steps simultaneously. WARNING\: Any step that will use the results of this Iterator operation will, by default, attempt to assign that step's inputs from a flow variable. If this is left checked, then the first element of the iterator will be used for every cycle of iteration. 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.b7bad816-751a-41ca-afe4-5135462a9f4e.transition.description=Web page was retrieved in less than timeout milliseconds. 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.bdba2455-af42-4069-831f-0e2571acb8a1.transition.description=Invalid URL\: web page could not be retrieved. 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.bde3358f-9ac7-49b9-a2c2-d2de3e073a92.transition.description=\ The web page was retrieved, but it took more than timeout milliseconds. 3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.c18c55c1-0607-46d2-9312-c5eb32fc51e8.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults".

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.description=
This flow crawls a website and finds pages with dead links. It then returns a report on which pages contain dead links, and what the dead links are.

Inputs\:
    notifyMethod - The method of notification (Write to File, Email, Display or None). This value is case-insensitive.
    baseURL - The list of URLs to be tested. Semicolon (;) is used as delimiter for this list.
    allowedDomains - A semicolon delimited list of domains that the flow is allowed to crawl through. This does not need to include the domain of baseURL.
    recursionDepth - The depth to which the crawler will continue to test linked pages.
Default value\: no recursion limit - this means that the crawler is allowed to recurse endlessly if the recurse input is "Yes".
Valid values\: natural numbers.
    timeout - How many milliseconds a page is given to respond before it is considered slow.
Default value\: 0 - this means that there is no response timeout and a page is considered "good" if it responds successfully.
    username - The username to use for authentication to the URLs.
    password - The password to use for basic authentication to the URLs.
    proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the URLs.
    proxyPort - A port on the proxy to connect to.
    proxyUsername - A username to use when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - A password to use when connecting to the proxy.
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. The default value will be provided if trustAllRoots is false.
Default\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and keystore is empty, keystorePassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. The default value will be provided if trustAllRoots is false.
Default\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.  If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    authType - The authentication type that this operation uses when trying to execute the request on the target server. 
Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
    useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value. 
Default value\: true.
    userAgent - If the HTTP header USER_AGENT needs to be overridden, pass in the value here.
    kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty the kdc (Key Distribution Center) and realm will get their values from the full domain name which is obtained from the url of the web server.
    headerNamesList - A list containing the names of headers that should be used for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - A list containing the values of headers that should be used for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - A list containing the names of query parameters that should be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - A list containing the values of query parameters that should be used for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - A delimiter that separates the elements in the names and values lists.
Default value\: , (comma).

Responses\:
success - The flow succeeded, no bad links were found.
failure - The flow failed.
diagnosed - Some bad links were found.

Note\:
1. If you need to specify the request header fields, consider using the "headerNamesList" and "headerValuesList" inputs. 
2. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, consider using the “queryNamesList” and “queryValuesList” inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the url (Example\: http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2). If you specify the same query parameter both through the "queryNamesList" and through the url input, then the value from the "queryValuesList" list will be used and not the one included in the url.
3. Currently, the only supported application server when using form-based authentication is Apache Tomcat.

3776ce1b-2fec-43c3-9aa4-a736266a7ce4.ec55931e-8d77-48a5-b148-4113ff7099b9.description=
Given a list of url references, this flow crawls from a webpage, through all linked webpages, and finds pages that reference a url in the list.

Inputs\:
baseURL - The url to start looking at.
allowedDomains - A semicolon delimited list of domains that the flow is allowed to crawl through. This does not need to include the domain of baseURL.
references - A semicolon delimited list of urls to find links to.
username - The username to use for basic authentication to the baseURL
password - The password to use for basic authentication to the baseURL
authType - The authentication type that this operation uses when trying to execute the request on the target server. Valid values\: basic, form, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
kerberosConfFile - The path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty the kdc (Key Distribution Center) and realm will get their values from the full domain name which is obtained from the url of the web server.
useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value. Default value\: true.
followRedirects - specifies whether or not the get command should automatically follow redirects. Default value is set to false.
proxy - a proxy to use when accessing the baseURL.
proxyPort - a port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - a username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - a password to use when connecting to the proxy.
encodeURL - Perform URL encoding. This is a boolean input. If a non-boolean value is specified, it will take the default value. Default value\: false.
userAgent - If the HTTP header USER_AGENT needs to be overridden, pass in the value here.
characterSet - The characterSet for HTTP Get request and response. Default is UTF-8.
trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.Default value\: false.
keystore - URL of the keystore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS client  authentication is not to be used.
keystorePassword - Password to unlock the keystore.
trustKeystore - URL of the truststore file or local path to it (e.g. %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts). It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore.
headerNamesList - A list containing the names of headers that should be used for the request. Example\: Accept,Content-Type
headerValuesList - A list containing the values of headers that should be used for the request. Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
queryNamesList - A list containing the names of query parameters that should be used for the request. Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2

referencing - Referencing URLs

failure - something went wrong.

Returns\:
A semicolon delimited list of urls that reference members of references.

Note\:
1. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, consider using the “queryNamesList” and “queryValuesList” inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the url (Example\: http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2). If you specify the same query parameter both through the "queryNamesList" and through the url input, then the value from the "queryValuesList" list will be used and not the one included in the url.
2. Currently, the only supported application server when using form-based authentication is Apache Tomcat.
